The paper proposes a novel kernel-based multi-task learning technique that automatically reveals structural inter-task relationships. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Additionally, the paper applies the proposed approach to pharmacological and collaborative filtering data, which are common topics in the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI), Computer Vision (cs.CV), and Natural Language Processing (cs.CL) sub-categories. Finally, the paper also involves optimization techniques, which are relevant to the Scientific Computing (cs.SI) sub-category.
